=== Fractal Rhythms: Definition and Properties

The preceding sections have built rhythmic objects without yet giving them a name. The iterates of the mirror rule, the Fibonacci word, its Pisot companion at ratio $sqrt(2)$, the Padovan morphism at ratio $rho$ — each has been produced and analysed on its own terms, but the common object they share has remained implicit. The present section lifts this object into view, proposes a definition that captures what the constructions of the preceding sections have in common, and identifies the musical properties that follow from this definition.

A _fractal rhythm_, in the sense developed in this chapter, is a rhythmic structure in which the swing character — the proportional relation between long and short durations — is consistent at every level of iteration. It is generated by a substitution rule that preserves a definite ratio between its constituent durations, and the irrational proportion that the rule selects — $sqrt(2)$, $phi.alt$, or $rho$ — is the measure of that consistency.#footnote[The formal definition, including the technical treatment of fixed points of substitution rules acting on infinite words and the spectral conditions that make the consistency rigorous, is given in @sec:formal-setup of Book IV.] What distinguishes a fractal rhythm from a rhythmic object that merely resembles its own structure across scales is precisely this consistency: the self-similarity is not an accidental resemblance between levels but a proportional identity enforced by the generative rule.

Three musical properties follow from this definition.

First, a fractal rhythm is _self-similar in the strict sense_: the swing pattern at one level of subdivision reappears at every finer level, in the same proportional relation. The musician who swings one pulse at a given ratio, then swings each element of the result at the same ratio, then swings each element of _that_ result again, is performing successive iterations of a substitution. The fractal rhythm is the limit of this process — what the swing becomes when it is allowed to descend through the hierarchy of subdivisions without losing its proportional character.

Second, a fractal rhythm carries an _irrational proportion_ as an essential feature. The ratio between durations is not a numerical approximation that the structure converges toward; it is the unique value that the rule can produce coherently at every level. A rational approximation of this ratio — even an extremely precise one — would not satisfy the consistency condition beyond a finite depth, because the small error between the rational and the true irrational would compound under iteration and push the rhythm out of its fractal regime. The irrationality of the proportion is structural, not asymptotic, and it is what makes the title of this chapter — _Fractal Rhythms and Irrational Proportions_ — describe a single object rather than two related ones.

Third, a fractal rhythm has, in practice, a _bounded depth_. The mathematical object is an infinite word; the musical object is a structure realised at a finite number of iteration levels, after which the finest subdivisions fall outside the window of rhythmic perception. The depth at which this boundary lies depends on the inflation of the rule and on the base tempo, and it varies systematically across the triad: the mirror, with the smallest inflation, supports the deepest recursion at a given tempo; the Pisot rules, with larger inflations, support correspondingly fewer levels. This bounded depth is not a defect of the framework but a feature of the rhythmic domain: fractal rhythms live at the intersection of what the substitution permits and what the perceiving listener can follow.#footnote[The quantitative analysis of perceptual depth — the formula relating inflation, tempo, and the number of admissible iteration levels within the groove window — is developed in @sec:perceptual-viability of Book IV.]

