Beyond these three structural properties, a fractal rhythm carries the _musical_ properties developed in the preceding sections. Its interleaving may be homogeneous (Fibonacci, Padovan) or clustered (mirror); its stability may be Pisot (self-correcting under perturbation) or non-Pisot (drifting); its harmonic neighbourhood may lie within the Pythagorean region (the mirror's $sqrt(2)$ iterate, made of octaves, fifths, and fourths) or outside it (Fibonacci's $phi.alt$, Padovan's $rho$, neither expressible as a Pythagorean ratio). These differences are not part of the definition but distinguishing features of the particular fractal rhythm at hand, and they constitute the axes along which the triad of @sec:triad is structurally organised.

It is worth situating this definition explicitly against a familiar object. The Western metric system of nested note values — whole, half, quarter, eighth, and so on — satisfies the formal definition of a fractal rhythm in a _degenerate_ sense: it is the fixed point of the elementary substitution $L arrow.r L L, S arrow.r S S$, and its ratio is the trivial value $1$. There is no inequality between letters, no swing at any level, and the harmonic neighbourhood is reduced to the octave. Western notation is thus a fractal rhythm with rational ratio $1$, consistent at every level but harmonically impoverished. The fractal rhythms constructed in this chapter are the _non-degenerate_ extensions of this structure: they preserve the self-similarity of the Western system while admitting inequality at each level, and the irrationality of their proportions is the price of this non-degeneracy.

Within the literature reviewed in @sec:state-of-research, this definition contributes a specific refinement. The fractal tradition of Brothers and the compositional tradition of Nørgård and Johnson have offered analytical frameworks and compositional techniques for self-similar musical structures; the combinatorial tradition of Carey, Clampitt, and Noll has developed the theory of Sturmian words and their morphisms in the context of scale theory. What the present chapter adds is the link between these traditions and the phenomenon of rhythmic swing examined in Chapter 3. A fractal rhythm, on the definition given here, is not merely a self-similar rhythmic object: it is a _swung_ rhythmic object whose swing is consistent at every scale, with the irrational proportion that characterises its consistency emerging from a musical constraint — the preservation of swing under iteration — rather than being imposed as an external mathematical choice.

With fractal rhythms defined, and with the triad of irrational proportions identified, the framework developed in this chapter is complete. The synthesis of these results within the broader topological perspective that the thesis as a whole moves toward is taken up in the next chapter.